You can use the [switch](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/switch) statement for comparing integers or characters in C++.

Allow fall through for multiple cases.

For your example:

```
switch (input) {
    case &#39;1&#39;:
    case &#39;3&#39;:
    case &#39;7&#39;:
        do_something();
        break;
    default:
        do_something_else();
        break;
}   
```

The compiler will (probably) generate code that uses a jump table, avoiding the need to test explicitly against each value. The values in the case labels have to be constant.

I think the canonical way is creating a set and check it with `find()`

    std::set&lt;int&gt; s;
    s.insert(...) 
    if (s.find(input) != s.end()) {
       //do stuff
    }

This will shorten the if condition, but you&#39;ll have to fill the set first. Depending on the situation, it could be more readeable with a long if.

This answer gives you the ability to do the same search for something beyond an integer:

    Foo some_array[n];
    // Populate array here...
    // If the object is not in the array, std::find returns the end of the range
    if( std::find(std::begin(some_array), std::end(some_array), item_to_look_for) != std::end(some_array) ) {
        //found!
    } else {
        //not found
    }

You could write your `if` statement like this:

    if (strchr(&quot;137&quot;, input))
    {
    }

You can use the [scope resolution operator](https://en.cppreference.com/w/cpp/language/qualified_lookup) with the parent class. e.g:

    #include &lt;iostream&gt;
    
    class A {
    public:
      virtual void foo() { std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;A&quot;; }
    };
    
    class B: public A {
    public:
      void foo() override { std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;B&quot;; }
    };
    
    class C: public B {
    public:
      void foo() override { 
        A::foo();
        B::foo();
        std::cout &lt;&lt; &quot;C&quot;; 
      }
    };
    
    int main() {
      C c;
      c.foo();
    }

As you are saying, that mocha is also printing the data into the console, this is likely the easiest way to get the test results.

### Simple approach

To simply mirror the IO of the browser including any data logged to console, you can enable the option `dumpio` when launching the browser:

```js
puppeteer.launch({ dumpio: true })
```

Quote from the docs for [`puppeteer.launch`][1]:

&gt; `dumpio` &lt;`boolean`&gt; Whether to pipe the browser process stdout and stderr into `process.stdout` and `process.stderr`. Defaults to `false`.

Be aware, that this will also print other information from the browser into the console. If you are looking only for the console data, you can use the second option.

### Only logging calls to `console.log`, etc.

To only get the data which is logged to `console.log` or `console.info`, etc. you can listen to the [`console`][2] event.

```js
page.on(&#39;console&#39;, consoleMessage =&gt; {
    console.log(consoleMessage.text());
    if (consoleMessage.type() === &#39;error&#39;) {
        // handle error output
    }
});
```

This way, you can grab all output going into the console. You can even use [`consoleMessage.type()`][3] to differentiate between error, warnings and normal output.


  [1]: https://github.com/GoogleChrome/puppeteer/blob/v1.19.0/docs/api.md#puppeteerlaunchoptions
  [2]: https://github.com/GoogleChrome/puppeteer/blob/v1.19.0/docs/api.md#event-console
  [3]: https://github.com/GoogleChrome/puppeteer/blob/v1.19.0/docs/api.md#consolemessagetype

